bib_record.title: Reaction Rates of the S-Process Neutron Sources 22-Ne(ALPHA,N)25-Mg and 13-C(ALPHA,N)16-O.

free_txt: - Abstract-
The Excitation Function of the S-Process Neutron Source
Reactions 22-Ne(A,N)25-Mg and 13-C(A,N)16-O has Been
Measured Using Improved Ion-Beam, Target, and Detection
Techniques, Reaching a Sensitivity Limit of 50
Picobarns in the Best Cases. For 22-Ne(A,N)25-Mg the
New Data Cover the Energy Range from Threshold (E-LAB =
570 KEV) Up to E-Lab= 2300 KeV. From these Experiments
Some of the Parameters of the 22-Ne(A,N)25-Mg
Resoances have Been Determined Using Unfolding
Techniques. A Resonance at About E=620 KeV Could
Clearly be Ascribed to the Background Reaction
11-B(A,N)14-N. The Excitation Function of
13-C(A,N)16-O has Been Measured Over the Energy Range
E-Lab= 350-1400 KeV, Where the Cross Section Varies
Over Eight Orders of Magnitude. The S-Factor at this
Reaction Indicates an Increase Toward Lower Energies,
Possibly Due to a State in 17-O Below the (13-C+ ALPHA)
Threshold Leading to a Higher Reaction Rate.  On the
Basis of the Experimental Data the Reaction Rates at
Helium-Burning Temperatures were Determined For these
Two Reactions: Both Rates are Increased Compared with
Previous Evaluations.
For 22-Ne(A,N)25-Mg the Sensitivity Limit was
Reached at About 5.E-10 Barn with an Improved 4-Pi
Neutron-Detector.  For 13-C(A,N)16-O the Sensitivity
Limit was an Order of Magnitude Still Lower Due to the
Effective Differential Measurement Procedure.  The
Design of the Detector [Two Concentric Circles of Eight
3-He Counters Each in a Polyethylene Moderator] Led to
An Absolute Efficiency of 37+/-1% in the Neon
Experiment [0< E-Lab < 1.5 Mev] and Allowed a Rough
Energy Measurement of the Neutrons by Taking Into
Account the Ratio of the Count Rates Registered from
The Inner and the Outer Counter Rings.
The Uncertainty is Given in Data Table Without
Any Analysis
Dr93 Data Set
Energy and Width of Observed Resonanses.
The References Regarding to Experimental Setup and
Procedures.
In the 22-Ne(A,N)25-Mg Experiment the Beam was Guided,
With Newly 100% Transmission Efficiency, Through Five
Apertures of the Windowless Gas Target System - Four
Pumping Stages- Into an Extended Target Chamber.  The
System was Filled with 99.8% Enriched 22-Ne Gas and the
Recirculating Gas was Continually Purified.
In the Case of 13-C(A,N)16-O, Special Targets For High
Currents were Made Using Enriched Elemental 13-C (99%)
On a Solid Copper Backing.  These Targets Could be
Reversed in Situ to Allow Accurate Background
Measurements by Letting the Beam Hit the Bare Backing
Material Instead of Tbe 13-C-Coated Backing.
